Maybe inherently was the wrong word. Though you can imagine a logger API that was like this:<p><pre><code>    typedef enum {
        CONSOLE_LOGGER,
        DATABASE_LOGGER,
        /* etc. */
    } LoggerType;

    void add_logger(LoggerType);
</code></pre>
In this API you&#x27;re constrained by what loggers you can add. It&#x27;s not the totally unchecked free-for-all that a callback-based API provides. The user is strictly unable to shoot themselves in the foot.<p>But this limits the expressive power that callbacks provide. Sorry I don&#x27;t have any other API recommendations. The only way I can think of to stay expressive while safeguarding against unintended abuse is to include code analysis.
